deck: Charlie Meyerson is a Chicago area radio personality and long time comics letter hack. His main contribution to comics is as a critic for the various major media outlets he's worked with. In the mid 80's he wrote an excellent series on the Comics Code Authority and Censorship for First Comics which ran in several of their magazines.
description:
Charles Meyerson started getting letters printed in comics when he was about 9 years old. (Herbie No. 7, February 1965 was his first.) He was a comics fan and letterhack during the same years as Kurt Busiek, T.M. Maple and Mark Evanier, who hired Meyerson as a columnist for the short-lived Marvelmania Monthly Magazine.

In the early 1980s, his longtime friend Mike Gold, then editor at the Chicago-area-based First Comics, drafted him to write a multi-part series of one page essays on the history and ramifications of the Comics Code Authority, and comics censorship in general. As a self-professed huge fan of Howard Chaykin's American Flagg series, Charlie helped write the text parts of the American Flagg Dossier backup feature during Flagg's initial run.

Charlie's been a Chicago-area radio personality for years, having delivered the news for the legendary progressive/alt-rock station WXRT-FM, and smooth-jazz station WNUA-FM. He went on to become a founding member of the breaking news team at the Chicago Tribune's website, he's won buckets of journalism awards, and he currently runs the online strategy consultant website company Meyerson Strategy. His pop-culture commentary on the blog part of his Meyerson Strategy website is not to be missed.
name: Charles Meyerson
